Web Scraping with R: get and combine Wikipedia tables

Yixin Wang

  • 1. Task
  • 2. Method
  • 3. Code
  • 4. Result and discussion

1. Task

Get the multiple tables about Spanish monarchs in wikipedia https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Spanish_monarchs and combine them to one.


The tedious work of copying and pasting multiple tables from Internet can be done with very few lines of R code. As a demonstration, we will tackle this task step by step.

2. Method

Scrape the web → select the useful nodes (in this case, table) → convert HTML tables into data frames → combine them

3. Code

#Packages
library(rvest) #functions: read_html, html_nudes, html_table
#Get the web and save it with read_html 
web <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Spanish_monarchs"
s <- read_html(web)

#With the selector "table", html_nodes will get all the HTML tables in the web
tab <- html_nodes(s, "table")

#The tables form a list
tab
## {xml_nodeset (13)}
##  [1] <table class="box-Expand_Spanish plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-no ...
##  [2] <table class="vertical-navbox vcard" style="float:right;clear:right ...
##  [3] <table class="infobox" style="font-size:93%; width: 147px;"><tbody> ...
##  [4] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
##  [5] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
##  [6] <table style="text-align:center; background:#FBDDBD; width:100%" cl ...
##  [7] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
##  [8] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
##  [9] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
## [10] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
## [11] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
## [12] <table cellspacing="0" style="text-align:center"><tbody>\n<tr>\n<th ...
## [13] <table class="nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner" st ...
#Select the tables that contain the information we need 
tab <- tab[c(4:5, 7:12)]

#Apply html_table to each element of the list and convert all the HTML tables into data frames 
tab <- lapply(tab, html_table)

#Combine the data frames into one data frame by row
tab <- do.call(rbind, tab)

4. Result and discussion

Although most work was done automatically, we did need to check which tables in the original web were really needed. The final table is in a wide form and needs further cleaning.
